# Writing

Two voice modes — pick one deliberately per artifact, don't blend them.

## Technical voice (default)

Used for: design write-ups, implementation explanations, README usage sections, API/behavior
docs.

Tone: concise, direct, precise, practical, minimal ornamentation, list-friendly,
non-patronizing.

Example: "`chezmoi apply` renders every managed template and copies changed targets into place;
it skips a `run_once_` script only when the script's content hash already matches what last ran."

## Narrative/conceptual voice (exception, not default)

Used for: project retrospectives, origin stories, historical commentary — reserved for
explicitly reflective/historical writing, not the default.

Tone: thoughtful, occasionally witty, reflective without becoming vague, readable and engaging.

Example: "The first draft of this pipeline assumed every AI tool could read the same file the
same way; it took an afternoon of broken parses to relearn that 'universal format' usually means
'nobody's format.'"

## No process narrative in state-describing docs

Keep task, ticket, PR, review-discussion, or session-specific narrative out of README/design/API
docs; describe the system as it is now, citing durable references where useful. That process
history belongs in the appropriate record (see `my-audit-trail`), or in a project retrospective
if genuinely worth preserving long-term.

## Out of scope

Code comments/docstrings (see `my-commenting`); commit messages, PR descriptions, Jira comments,
incident notes (see `my-audit-trail`); terse operational/status responses (no styling needed).
